Partitions, and partition tables — MBR versus GPT.

A partition is a contiguous slice of a disk, with its own boundaries. Why bother slicing a disk up? A few reasons: to put multiple filesystems on one disk, say one for slash and one for slash-home; to reserve space for swap or recovery; to dual-boot two operating systems; and because smaller filesystems are faster to check and repair.

Partitions are described by a partition table, which lives right at the start of the disk. And there are two formats you need to know, MBR and GPT. MBR, the master boot record, is the old standard. It allows up to four primary partitions, it caps disk size at two terabytes, and it goes with legacy BIOS booting. It's still all over older systems. GPT, the GUID partition table, is the modern standard. It allows up to a hundred and twenty-eight partitions, has essentially no practical size limit, keeps a backup copy of the table at the end of the disk for redundancy, and is required by UEFI firmware, which is what modern PCs and servers use. The guidance is simple: use GPT for any new disk unless you have a specific reason not to. You can check which one a disk uses by running sudo parted, the device, print, and looking for "Partition Table: gpt."

Two tools do the partitioning. The first is fdisk, the classic interactive one. Inside it, p prints the current table, n makes a new partition, d deletes one, t changes a partition's type, and w writes your changes and exits. The second is parted, which is newer, handles both MBR and GPT, and, importantly, has a non-interactive command form you can script. For example, parted with mklabel gpt creates a fresh GPT table, and mkpart creates a partition spanning a percentage range of the disk.

And now the warning, and it's a serious one: any partition change can destroy data. Always back up first. Never partition a disk that holds live data without a verified backup, and always, always triple-check the device path, slash-dev-sda versus slash-dev-sdb, before you press write. Finally, after writing partitions, run partprobe so the kernel re-reads the partition table, and then lsblk to confirm the new layout is really there.
